{"title_page": "Yuli Edelstein", "text_new": "{{pp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Israeli politician and Speaker of the Knesset}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox member of the Knesset\n|image= \u05d9\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d0\u05d3\u05dc\u05e9\u05d8\u05d9\u05d9\u05df - \u05ea\u05de\u05d5\u05e0\u05ea \u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05e4\u05d9\u05dc.jpg\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|8|5|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Chernivtsi]], [[Soviet Union]]\n|Year of Aliyah = 1987\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|Knesset(s) = [[1996 Israeli legislative election|14]], [[1999 Israeli legislative election|15]], [[2003 Israeli legislative election|16]], [[2006 Israeli legislative election|17]], [[2009 Israeli legislative election|18]], [[2013 Israeli legislative election|19]], [[2015 Israeli legislative election|20]], [[April 2019 Israeli legislative election|21]], [[September 2019 Israeli legislative election|22]], [[2020 Israeli legislative election|23]]\n|party1 = [[Yisrael BaAliyah]]\n|partyyears1 = 1996\u20132003\n|party2 = [[Likud]]\n|partyyears2 = 2003\u20132006\n|party3 = [[Likud]]\n|partyyears3 = 2007\u2013\n|minister1 = [[Immigrant Absorption Minister of Israel|Minister of Immigrant Absorption]]\n|ministeryears1 = 1996\u20131999\n|minister2 = {{nowrap|[[Information and Diaspora Minister of Israel|Minister of Information & Diaspora]]}}\n|ministeryears2 = 2009\u20132013\n|otherroles1 = [[List of Knesset speakers|Speaker of the Knesset]]\n|otherrolesyears1 = 2013\u20132020\n|}}\n\n'''Yuli-Yoel Edelstein''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d9\u05d5\u05bc\u05dc\u05b4\u05d9\u05be\u05d9\u05d5\u05b9\u05d0\u05b5\u05dc \u05d0\u05b5\u05d3\u05b6\u05dc\u05b0\u05e9\u05b0\u05d8\u05b5\u05d9\u05d9\u05df}}, {{lang-ru|link=no|\u042e\u0301\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u042e\u0301\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u042d\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0442\u0435\u0301\u0439\u043d}}, {{lang-uk|\u042e\u0301\u043b\u0456\u0439 \u042e\u0301\u0440\u0456\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0415\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0442\u0435\u0301\u0439\u043d}}, born 5 August 1958) is an [[Israel]]i politician. One of the most prominent [[refuseniks]] in the Soviet Union, he was [[List of Knesset speakers|Speaker of the Knesset]] from 2013 until his resignation on 25 March 2020.\n\n==Early life==\nYuli Edelstein was born in [[Chernivtsi]] in the [[Soviet Union]] (now [[Ukraine]]) to a Jewish family. His mother, Anita Edelstein, was Jewish, while his father, Yuri Edelstein, is the son of a Jewish father and Christian mother. Both converted to Christianity, and Yuri is now a [[Russian Orthodox Church|Russian Orthodox]] priest in Karabanovo of [[Kostroma Oblast]] named Father Georgy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/apr/22/world/la-fg-russia-church-scandal-20120422|title=Russian Orthodox Church is in spiritual crisis, critics say|author= Sergei L. Loiko|work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |date=22 April 2012 |accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jta.org/1997/11/13/news-opinion/russian-priest-visits-son-israels-absorption-minister |title=Russian priest visits son: Israel's absorption minister|agency= [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |date=13 November 1997 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>  While his parents taught at universities in the countryside, Edelstein was raised by his maternal grandparents. His grandfather had taught himself [[Hebrew]] at the age of 70 and used to listen to the [[Voice of Israel]] on a shortwave radio. When Edelstein's grandfather died, Yuli began to study Hebrew and read books such as ''[[Exodus (Uris novel)|Exodus]]'' by [[Leon Uris]], which inspired him.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/06/21/world/from-siberia-to-israeli-cabinet-no-he-s-not-sharansky.html |title=From Siberia to Israeli Cabinet (No, he's not Sharansky) |work= [[The New York Times]] |author=Deborah Sontag |date=21 June 1999 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1977, during his second year of university, Edelstein applied for an exit visa to [[Aliyah|immigrate]] to Israel. Turned down, he began to associate with a small group of Hebrew teachers who held classes in their apartments.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\nIn 1979, he was expelled from the university and suffered harassment by the [[KGB]] and local police. During this time, he found odd jobs as a street cleaner, security guard, and more.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\nIn 1984, he and other Hebrew teachers were arrested on fabricated charges, Edelstein himself being charged with possession of drugs,<ref>Encyclopaedia Judaica Year Book. 1986. p.366</ref><ref>\"When They Come for Us, We'll Be Gone: The Epic Struggle to Save Soviet Jewry\". By Gal Beckerman. Chapter 12</ref><ref>Philip Spiegel. \"Triumph over tyranny: the heroic campaigns that saved 2,000,000 Soviet Jews\". p. 157</ref><ref>Maxim Shrayer. Leaving Russia: A Jewish Story. p.158</ref><ref>The Listener. Volume 113. p.43. British Broadcasting Corporation, 1985.</ref><ref>The Prosecution of Demonstrators Outside the Soviet Embassy: Hearing Before the Subcommittee on Administrative Practice and Procedure of the Committee on the Judiciary, United States Senate, Ninety-ninth Congress, Second Session, on Citizens Exercising Their Constitutionally Protected Rights, Protesting the Brutal Treating of Human Beings in Faraway Lands, May 15, 1986. p.30</ref> and sentenced to three years. He was then sent to [[Siberia]]n [[Corrective labor colony|penal colonies]] and did hard labor, first in [[Buryat Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic|Buryatia]] and then in [[Novosibirsk]]. He broke several bones after falling from a construction tower. He was due to be transferred back to Buryatia, but his wife, Tanya, threatened to go on [[hunger strike]] if he was returned there.<ref name=\"ja\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jewishagency.org/JewishAgency/English/Jewish+Education/Compelling+Content/Eye+on+Israel/Aliyah/40/edelstein.htm |title=Yuli Edelstein |publisher= [[The Jewish Agency for Israel]] |author=Dina Goldman |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nEdelstein was released in May 1987,<ref name=\"ja\"/> on the eve of [[Israeli Independence Day]], the next to last of the ''[[refusenik]]s'' to be freed.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> He then [[aliyah|immigrated to Israel]], moving to the [[West Bank]] settlement of [[Alon Shvut]]. He did his national service in the [[Israel Defense Forces]], attaining the rank of [[Corporal]].<ref>[https://knesset.gov.il/mk/eng/mk_eng.asp?mk_individual_id_t=1 Particulars] Knesset</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:Flickr - The Israel Project - Israel Information Minister Yuli Edelstien briefs reporters where 3 civilians were killed by a Hamas rocket..jpg|thumb|Edelstein as Information Minister, briefing reporters at site of Hamas rocket attack, 2012]]\nInitially a member of the [[National Religious Party]] and a vice-president of Zionist Forum, Edelstein founded the [[Yisrael BaAliyah]] party together with fellow Soviet dissident [[Natan Sharansky]]. He was elected to the Knesset in [[1996 Israeli legislative election|1996]], and was appointed [[Immigrant Absorption Minister of Israel|Minister of Immigrant Absorption]] in [[Benjamin Netanyahu]]'s [[Likud]]-led [[Twenty-seventh government of Israel|government]].<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> He was re-elected in [[1999 Israeli legislative election|1999]], and was appointed Deputy Immigrant Absorption Minister by [[Ariel Sharon]] in 2001.\n\nHe retained his seat in the [[2003 Israeli legislative election|2003 elections]], shortly after which Yisrael BaAliyah merged into Likud. Although Edelstein lost his seat in the [[2006 Israeli legislative election|2006 elections]], in which Likud was reduced to 12 seats (Edelstein was 14th on the party's list), he re-entered the Knesset as a replacement for [[Dan Naveh]] in February 2007. He retained his seat in the [[2009 Israeli legislative election|2009 elections]] after being placed twelfth on the party's list, and was appointed [[Information and Diaspora Minister of Israel|Minister of Information and Diaspora]] in the [[Cabinet of Israel|Netanyahu government]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/netanyahu-sworn-in-as-israel-s-prime-minister-1.273265|title=Netanyahu sworn in as Israel's prime minister|work= [[Haaretz]] |date= 1 April 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2013 Israeli legislative election|2013 elections]], he became Speaker of the Knesset.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Yuli-Edelstein-appointed-as-new-Knesset-Speaker|title=Yuli Edelstein appointed as new Knesset Speaker |work= [[The Jerusalem Post]] |author=Lahav Harkov  |date= 14 March 2013 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref> On 25 March 2020, he stepped down as the Speaker.<ref>https://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-5701258,00.html</ref>\n\n==Statements==\nIn December 2014, in an interview with ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', Edelstein warned world leaders against creating a Palestinian state that he thought would go to war with Israel.<ref name=\"jpost1214\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Arab-Israeli-Conflict/Edelstein-Wrong-to-create-Palestinian-state-wed-have-to-attack-386056|title=Edelstein: Wrong to create Palestinian state Israel would have to attack |work= [[The Jerusalem Post]] |author1= Gil Hoffman|author2=Lahav Harkov  |date=29 December 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn the same interview, Edelstein stated that he believes in Israeli-Palestinian coexistence. In 2014, he was one of several Members of the Knesset (MK) who submitted complaints against Arab-Israeli [[Haneen Zoabi]] for supporting Hamas,  which led to her six-month suspension. \u201cI have been in the Knesset for almost 19 years,\u201d Edelstein said. \u201cI remember Arab MKs joining me at the March of the Living and proposing social-oriented legislation with me. That is definitely not Zoabi. I believe in coexistence and fighting against those who harm it and I think that Zoabi\u2019s words and actions hurt coexistence. People hear her and think all Arabs must hate us and want to kill us. That is unhealthy, and we have to put an end to it.\u201d\n\nEdelstein criticized Jewish U.S. presidential candidate [[Bernie Sanders]] for saying that U.S. military aid to Israel should instead be diverted toward humanitarian aid to Palestinians in the Gaza Strip. Edelstein said that Sanders should 'stop talking nonsense'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Israel's Knesset Speaker to Bernie Sanders: 'Stop Talking Nonsense'|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israel-s-knesset-speaker-to-bernie-sanders-stop-talking-nonsense-1.8054665|date=29 October 2019|accessdate=31 October 2019|publisher=[[Haaretz]]|author=Allison Kaplan Sommer}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAfter leaving Alon Shvut, Edelstein moved to [[Neve Daniel]], another West Bank settlement. He was married to Tatiana (Tanya) Edelstein, who was a Zionist activist, for 33 years. They met in the Soviet Union when she attended a Hebrew class he was teaching. After immigrating to Israel, she worked as a civil engineer at the [[Civil Aviation Authority of Israel|Civil Aviation Authority]]. Tanya and Yuli Edelstein had two children together. In 2014, Tanya died of cancer at the age of 63.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/tanya-edelstein-wife-of-knesset-speaker-dies-at-63/|title=Tanya Edelstein, wife of Knesset speaker, dies at 63|work= [[Times of Israel]]|author=Lazar Berman |date= January 24, 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Edelstein married [[Irina Nevzlin]], chair of the board of Directors of The Museum of the Jewish People at [[Beit Hatfutsot]] and President of the NADAV Foundation.\n\n== Criticism ==\n{{see|2020 Israeli constitutional crisis}}\nThe long-term project of subsidizing housing for elderly [[Repatriation|migrants]] prepared by [[Ministry of Aliyah and Integration|Israel Ministry of Absorption]] under his supervision and cooperation with Ministry of Construction raised controversy over expenditures overrun incurred by the project. Edelstein claimed that the investigative commission found such claims unsubstantiated.<ref>[http://www.newsru.co.il/arch/israel/28jul2008/edelstein8011.html \u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044c\u044e \u042d\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0442\u0435\u0439\u043d\u0430 \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0435 NEWSru.co.il]:''\u041f\u043e \u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043c \u0434\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u042d\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0442\u0435\u0439\u043d\u0430, \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0433\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u044b \u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0438 \u0440\u0435\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0434\u0430\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0430\u044e\u0442\u0441\u044f \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u044b, \u043d\u043e \u0434\u0432\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0440\u044f\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043d\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u044d\u0442\u0438 \u0443\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f, \u0445\u043e\u0442\u044f \u044d\u0442\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u00ab\u041c\u0438\u043a\u0431\u0430\u0446\u0435\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u044e\u0440\u00bb.''</ref>\n\nHis attempts to wait with the new Knesset Speaker vote to after the coalition talks, following the 23rd Knesset election of 2020. When the Israeli Supreme Court ordered him to hold the vote. Edelstein decided to resign instead of fulfilling the order, for which he was harshly criticized.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Genesis Prize]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{MKlink|id=1}}\n*[http://www.edelstein.org.il/english/ Yuli Edelstein \u2013 Web Page]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Reuven Rivlin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Knesset speakers|Speaker of the Knesset]]|years=2013\u20132020}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Current MKs}}\n{{KnessetSpeakers}}\n{{Israeli Immigrant Absorption Ministers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Edelstein, Yuli-Yoel}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bukovina Jews]]\n[[Category:Deputy ministers of Israel]]\n[[Category:Deputy Speakers of the Knesset]]\n[[Category:Israeli people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Israeli people of Ukrainian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Alon Shvut]]\n[[Category:Israeli settlers]]\n[[Category:Jewish Israeli politicians]]\n[[Category:Likud politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the 14th Knesset (1996\u20131999)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 15th Knesset (1999\u20132003)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 16th Knesset (2003\u20132006)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 17th Knesset (2006\u20132009)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 18th Knesset (2009\u20132013)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 19th Knesset (2013\u20132015)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 20th Knesset (2015\u20132019)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 21st Knesset (2019)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 22nd Knesset (2019\u20132020)]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Israel]]\n[[Category:People from Chernivtsi]]\n[[Category:Refuseniks]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Knesset]]\n[[Category:Soviet emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:Soviet Jews]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:Yisrael BaAliyah politicians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Skanderbeg (1990\u2013)]]\n[[Category:Members of the 23rd Knesset (2020\u2013)]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Israeli politician and Speaker of the Knesset}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox member of the Knesset\n|image= \u05d9\u05d5\u05dc\u05d9 \u05d0\u05d3\u05dc\u05e9\u05d8\u05d9\u05d9\u05df - \u05ea\u05de\u05d5\u05e0\u05ea \u05e4\u05e8\u05d5\u05e4\u05d9\u05dc.jpg\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|8|5|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Chernivtsi]], [[Soviet Union]]\n|Year of Aliyah = 1987\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|Knesset(s) = [[1996 Israeli legislative election|14]], [[1999 Israeli legislative election|15]], [[2003 Israeli legislative election|16]], [[2006 Israeli legislative election|17]], [[2009 Israeli legislative election|18]], [[2013 Israeli legislative election|19]], [[2015 Israeli legislative election|20]], [[April 2019 Israeli legislative election|21]], [[September 2019 Israeli legislative election|22]], [[2020 Israeli legislative election|23]]\n|party1 = [[Yisrael BaAliyah]]\n|partyyears1 = 1996\u20132003\n|party2 = [[Likud]]\n|partyyears2 = 2003\u20132006\n|party3 = [[Likud]]\n|partyyears3 = 2007\u2013\n|minister1 = [[Immigrant Absorption Minister of Israel|Minister of Immigrant Absorption]]\n|ministeryears1 = 1996\u20131999\n|minister2 = {{nowrap|[[Information and Diaspora Minister of Israel|Minister of Information & Diaspora]]}}\n|ministeryears2 = 2009\u20132013\n|otherroles1 = [[List of Knesset speakers|Speaker of the Knesset]]\n|otherrolesyears1 = 2013\u20132020\n|}}\n\n'''Yuli-Yoel Edelstein''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05d9\u05d5\u05bc\u05dc\u05b4\u05d9\u05be\u05d9\u05d5\u05b9\u05d0\u05b5\u05dc \u05d0\u05b5\u05d3\u05b6\u05dc\u05b0\u05e9\u05b0\u05d8\u05b5\u05d9\u05d9\u05df}}, {{lang-ru|link=no|\u042e\u0301\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u042e\u0301\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u042d\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0442\u0435\u0301\u0439\u043d}}, {{lang-uk|\u042e\u0301\u043b\u0456\u0439 \u042e\u0301\u0440\u0456\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0415\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0442\u0435\u0301\u0439\u043d}}, born 5 August 1958) is an [[Israel]]i politician. One of the most prominent [[refuseniks]] in the Soviet Union, he was [[List of Knesset speakers|Speaker of the Knesset]] from 2013 until his resignation on 25 March 2020.\n\n==Early life==\nYuli Edelstein was born in [[Chernivtsi]] in the [[Soviet Union]] (now [[Ukraine]]) to a Jewish family. His mother, Anita Edelstein, was Jewish, while his father, Yuri Edelstein, is the son of a Jewish father and Christian mother. Both converted to Christianity, and Yuri is now a [[Russian Orthodox Church|Russian Orthodox]] priest in Karabanovo of [[Kostroma Oblast]] named Father Georgy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/apr/22/world/la-fg-russia-church-scandal-20120422|title=Russian Orthodox Church is in spiritual crisis, critics say|author= Sergei L. Loiko|work= [[Los Angeles Times]] |date=22 April 2012 |accessdate=14 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jta.org/1997/11/13/news-opinion/russian-priest-visits-son-israels-absorption-minister |title=Russian priest visits son: Israel's absorption minister|agency= [[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]] |date=13 November 1997 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>  While his parents taught at universities in the countryside, Edelstein was raised by his maternal grandparents. His grandfather had taught himself [[Hebrew]] at the age of 70 and used to listen to the [[Voice of Israel]] on a shortwave radio. When Edelstein's grandfather died, Yuli began to study Hebrew and read books such as ''[[Exodus (Uris novel)|Exodus]]'' by [[Leon Uris]], which inspired him.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/06/21/world/from-siberia-to-israeli-cabinet-no-he-s-not-sharansky.html |title=From Siberia to Israeli Cabinet (No, he's not Sharansky) |work= [[The New York Times]] |author=Deborah Sontag |date=21 June 1999 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1977, during his second year of university, Edelstein applied for an exit visa to [[Aliyah|immigrate]] to Israel. Turned down, he began to associate with a small group of Hebrew teachers who held classes in their apartments.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\nIn 1979, he was expelled from the university and suffered harassment by the [[KGB]] and local police. During this time, he found odd jobs as a street cleaner, security guard, and more.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\nIn 1984, he and other Hebrew teachers were arrested on fabricated charges, Edelstein himself being charged with possession of drugs,<ref>Encyclopaedia Judaica Year Book. 1986. p.366</ref><ref>\"When They Come for Us, We'll Be Gone: The Epic Struggle to Save Soviet Jewry\". By Gal Beckerman. Chapter 12</ref><ref>Philip Spiegel. \"Triumph over tyranny: the heroic campaigns that saved 2,000,000 Soviet Jews\". p. 157</ref><ref>Maxim Shrayer. Leaving Russia: A Jewish Story. p.158</ref><ref>The Listener. Volume 113. p.43. British Broadcasting Corporation, 1985.</ref><ref>The Prosecution of Demonstrators Outside the Soviet Embassy: Hearing Before the Subcommittee on Administrative Practice and Procedure of the Committee on the Judiciary, United States Senate, Ninety-ninth Congress, Second Session, on Citizens Exercising Their Constitutionally Protected Rights, Protesting the Brutal Treating of Human Beings in Faraway Lands, May 15, 1986. p.30</ref> and sentenced to three years. He was then sent to [[Siberia]]n [[Corrective labor colony|penal colonies]] and did hard labor, first in [[Buryat Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic|Buryatia]] and then in [[Novosibirsk]]. He broke several bones after falling from a construction tower. He was due to be transferred back to Buryatia, but his wife, Tanya, threatened to go on [[hunger strike]] if he was returned there.<ref name=\"ja\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jewishagency.org/JewishAgency/English/Jewish+Education/Compelling+Content/Eye+on+Israel/Aliyah/40/edelstein.htm |title=Yuli Edelstein |publisher= [[The Jewish Agency for Israel]] |author=Dina Goldman |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nEdelstein was released in May 1987,<ref name=\"ja\"/> on the eve of [[Israeli Independence Day]], the next to last of the ''[[refusenik]]s'' to be freed.<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> He then [[aliyah|immigrated to Israel]], moving to the [[West Bank]] settlement of [[Alon Shvut]]. He did his national service in the [[Israel Defense Forces]], attaining the rank of [[Corporal]].<ref>[https://knesset.gov.il/mk/eng/mk_eng.asp?mk_individual_id_t=1 Particulars] Knesset</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:Flickr - The Israel Project - Israel Information Minister Yuli Edelstien briefs reporters where 3 civilians were killed by a Hamas rocket..jpg|thumb|Edelstein as Information Minister, briefing reporters at site of Hamas rocket attack, 2012]]\nInitially a member of the [[National Religious Party]] and a vice-president of Zionist Forum, Edelstein founded the [[Yisrael BaAliyah]] party together with fellow Soviet dissident [[Natan Sharansky]]. He was elected to the Knesset in [[1996 Israeli legislative election|1996]], and was appointed [[Immigrant Absorption Minister of Israel|Minister of Immigrant Absorption]] in [[Benjamin Netanyahu]]'s [[Likud]]-led [[Twenty-seventh government of Israel|government]].<ref name=\"nytimes\"/> He was re-elected in [[1999 Israeli legislative election|1999]], and was appointed Deputy Immigrant Absorption Minister by [[Ariel Sharon]] in 2001.\n\nHe retained his seat in the [[2003 Israeli legislative election|2003 elections]], shortly after which Yisrael BaAliyah merged into Likud. Although Edelstein lost his seat in the [[2006 Israeli legislative election|2006 elections]], in which Likud was reduced to 12 seats (Edelstein was 14th on the party's list), he re-entered the Knesset as a replacement for [[Dan Naveh]] in February 2007. He retained his seat in the [[2009 Israeli legislative election|2009 elections]] after being placed twelfth on the party's list, and was appointed [[Information and Diaspora Minister of Israel|Minister of Information and Diaspora]] in the [[Cabinet of Israel|Netanyahu government]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/news/netanyahu-sworn-in-as-israel-s-prime-minister-1.273265|title=Netanyahu sworn in as Israel's prime minister|work= [[Haaretz]] |date= 1 April 2009 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[2013 Israeli legislative election|2013 elections]], he became Speaker of the Knesset.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Breaking-News/Yuli-Edelstein-appointed-as-new-Knesset-Speaker|title=Yuli Edelstein appointed as new Knesset Speaker |work= [[The Jerusalem Post]] |author=Lahav Harkov  |date= 14 March 2013 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March 2020, he stepped down as the Speaker of the Knesset. <ref>https://www.ynet.co.il/articles/0,7340,L-5701258,00.html</ref>\n\n==Statements==\nIn December 2014, in an interview with ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'', Edelstein warned world leaders against creating a Palestinian state that he thought would go to war with Israel.<ref name=\"jpost1214\">{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Arab-Israeli-Conflict/Edelstein-Wrong-to-create-Palestinian-state-wed-have-to-attack-386056|title=Edelstein: Wrong to create Palestinian state Israel would have to attack |work= [[The Jerusalem Post]] |author1= Gil Hoffman|author2=Lahav Harkov  |date=29 December 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn the same interview, Edelstein stated that he believes in Israeli-Palestinian coexistence. In 2014, he was one of several Members of the Knesset (MK) who submitted complaints against Arab-Israeli [[Haneen Zoabi]] for supporting Hamas,  which led to her six-month suspension. \u201cI have been in the Knesset for almost 19 years,\u201d Edelstein said. \u201cI remember Arab MKs joining me at the March of the Living and proposing social-oriented legislation with me. That is definitely not Zoabi. I believe in coexistence and fighting against those who harm it and I think that Zoabi\u2019s words and actions hurt coexistence. People hear her and think all Arabs must hate us and want to kill us. That is unhealthy, and we have to put an end to it.\u201d\n\nEdelstein criticized Jewish U.S. presidential candidate [[Bernie Sanders]] for saying that U.S. military aid to Israel should instead be diverted toward humanitarian aid to Palestinians in the Gaza Strip. Edelstein said that Sanders should 'stop talking nonsense'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Israel's Knesset Speaker to Bernie Sanders: 'Stop Talking Nonsense'|url=https://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/.premium-israel-s-knesset-speaker-to-bernie-sanders-stop-talking-nonsense-1.8054665|date=29 October 2019|accessdate=31 October 2019|publisher=[[Haaretz]]|author=Allison Kaplan Sommer}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAfter leaving Alon Shvut, Edelstein moved to [[Neve Daniel]], another West Bank settlement. He was married to Tatiana (Tanya) Edelstein, who was a Zionist activist, for 33 years. They met in the Soviet Union when she attended a Hebrew class he was teaching. After immigrating to Israel, she worked as a civil engineer at the [[Civil Aviation Authority of Israel|Civil Aviation Authority]]. Tanya and Yuli Edelstein had two children together. In 2014, Tanya died of cancer at the age of 63.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/tanya-edelstein-wife-of-knesset-speaker-dies-at-63/|title=Tanya Edelstein, wife of Knesset speaker, dies at 63|work= [[Times of Israel]]|author=Lazar Berman |date= January 24, 2014 |accessdate=14 March 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Edelstein married [[Irina Nevzlin]], chair of the board of Directors of The Museum of the Jewish People at [[Beit Hatfutsot]] and President of the NADAV Foundation.\n\n== Criticism ==\n{{see|2020 Israeli constitutional crisis}}\nThe long-term project of subsidizing housing for elderly [[Repatriation|migrants]] prepared by [[Ministry of Aliyah and Integration|Israel Ministry of Absorption]] under his supervision and cooperation with Ministry of Construction raised controversy over expenditures overrun incurred by the project. Edelstein claimed that the investigative commission found such claims unsubstantiated.<ref>[http://www.newsru.co.il/arch/israel/28jul2008/edelstein8011.html \u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044c\u044e \u042d\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0442\u0435\u0439\u043d\u0430 \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0435 NEWSru.co.il]:''\u041f\u043e \u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043c \u0434\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u042d\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0442\u0435\u0439\u043d\u0430, \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0433\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u044b \u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0441\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0438 \u0440\u0435\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0434\u0430\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0430\u044e\u0442\u0441\u044f \u043c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u044b, \u043d\u043e \u0434\u0432\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0440\u044f\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u043d\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u044d\u0442\u0438 \u0443\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f, \u0445\u043e\u0442\u044f \u044d\u0442\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u00ab\u041c\u0438\u043a\u0431\u0430\u0446\u0435\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u044e\u0440\u00bb.''</ref>\n\nHis attempts to wait with the new Knesset Speaker vote to after the coalition talks, following the 23rd Knesset election of 2020. When the Israeli Supreme Court ordered him to hold the vote. Edelstein decided to resign instead of fulfilling the order, for which he was harshly criticized.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Genesis Prize]]\n\n